message.content:
After “rolling‐up” only those entries that affect the income statement – namely the sale transactions (which “already” record their profit result), the expense transactions (including financial, sales, administrative and depreciation entries) and the “interest receivables” (which add if positive and subtract if negative) – the net (or “before‐tax”) profit comes out to be approximately –849551.81.

Below we describe our reasoning briefly.

1. We ignore balance‐sheet entries such as “Initial”, “Fixed Assets Purchase”, “Purchase”, “Transfers” because they do not affect profit.
2. For “Sale” entries the “profit” field is used (it is the “result” of that sale after subtracting cost of goods).
3. For each “Expense” row (be it sales, administrative, financial or “Depreciation”), we subtract its “amount” (because these costs reduce profit).
4. For “Interest Receivables” rows we add their amount (or subtract if the value is negative).
5. When summing over all such rows – the positive sale “profit” items plus interest and then subtracting all various expense amounts – the final result is –849551.81.

Thus the final “Profit Before Tax” is –849551.81.
